A stable sort is a sorting algorithm that preserves the relative order of equal elements in the sorted output as they appeared in the input. That is, if two elements have the same key (i.e., the value used for sorting), a stable sort will ensure that the element which appeared first in the original list will also appear first in the sorted list.

Java uses the Dual Pivot QuickSort algorithm for sorting arrays of primitive types. It is efficient but unstable, meaning it does not maintain the relative order of equal elements.

Collections.sort() uses the MergeSort algorithm (or a hybrid of TimSort), which is stable, meaning it preserves the relative order of equal elements in a collection.

The Comparable interface is implemented by a class to define the natural order of its objects. If a custom order is needed, the Comparator interface is used.

Arrays.sort() uses Dual Pivot QuickSort, which has a time complexity of O(n log n) for sorting primitive arrays.

The time complexity to reverse the elements of an array of primitive data types is O(n), where n is the length of the array.

If a non-primitive type does not implement Comparable, then Collections.sort() requires a Comparator to define how the elements should be sorted.

Collections.sort() uses TimSort, a hybrid sorting algorithm that combines MergeSort and InsertionSort. This ensures stable sorting of non-primitive types in Java.

Arrays.sort(arr, 1, 1);
  The range is from index 1 (inclusive) to 1 (exclusive)
  This is an empty range, so no sorting happens
  Array remains: {1, 5, 3, 4}
arr.toString()
  Arrays in Java do not override toString()
  So it prints the object reference, not the contents

The Arrays.sort(arr, 1, 4) method sorts the subarray starting from index 1 up to (but not including) index 4. It sorts the elements {5, 3, 4} in ascending order, resulting in {3, 4, 5}. Therefore, the modified array becomes [1, 3, 4, 5].
